Simple, yet complex. Scalak is the kind of puzzle game that has one key 
idea, executed fantastically without cramming too many more concepts into 
one game. It's reminiscent of the Portal games in both its "learn by 
doing/trying" gameplay as well as its immensely fulfilling reward of 
feeling like a genius just because you solved long puzzle. I lay in bed for 
2+ hours absorbed by this game, I'm nearly done, I think, but the puzzles 
are now taking much longer to complete, so I will leave it till tomorrow to 
finish the remaining few puzzles I have to solve. Absolutely recommend this 
game if you're into the whole "Simple, but complex" type of puzzle games, 
the kind where a very simple concept is taken and built up into something 
challenging, but not impossibly so. The graphics are not super flashy, but 
they absolutely don't need to be, nor do I feel they should be. The 
graphics shown matches the simplicity of the game. My only real complaint 
would be that the rotation controls seemed to work extremely 
inconsistently, with puzzles rotating an entirely different direction to 
the one I swipe in here and there, but that could very well be a 
device-specific problem and not a fault of the game itself!
